          "type": "thinking",
          "thinking": "Let me implement the reactive system based on the spec.\n\nKey points:\n1. `InputCell` - stores a value, when setValue is called, propagates changes\n2. `ComputeCell` - depends on other cells, recomputes automatically, supports callbacks\n3. `CallbackCell` - stores collected callback results\n\nThe main challenge is:\n- Diamond dependencies: if A depends on B and C, and both B and C depend on input X, when X changes, A should only fire callbacks once\n- Callbacks only fire when value actually changes after full propagation\n\nApproach:\n- Use a simple observer pattern\n- InputCell notifies its subscribers when setValue is called\n\n\n- ComputeCell subscribes to its dependencies and recomputes when they change\n- When propagating changes, I'll track which cells have been updated and fire callbacks only after the system stabilizes\n\nWhen `InputCell.setValue` is called, I'll update the value, then recursively recompute all dependent ComputeCells in order, collecting which ones actually changed, and finally fire callbacks only for those cells that had new values.\n\nI'm setting up a system where each cell maintains a list of dependents, and during propagation I'll traverse from the changed input cell to find all affected cells and recompute them in the right order.\n\nBuilding the InputCell and propagation logic... I see the issue with diamond dependencies—a cell might be reachable through multiple paths, so I need to ensure it's only computed once and after all its dependencies are ready. The cleanest approach is to assign each cell a level based on its dependency depth, then process affected cells in level order.\n\nImplementing the level-based system... Registering each input cell as a dependent so they can notify this compute cell when their values change, then implementing the propagation logic where input cells trigger updates through their dependents and callbacks get notified of any actual value changes. Finishing the dependency propagation logic...\n\nI need to make sure InputCell has a way to register dependents, and I'm realizing the level calculation needs to account for InputCell having an implicit level of 0, while ComputeCell levels are determined by their dependencies. The propagate function will need access to cell internals, so I'll use underscore-prefixed methods to indicate they're internal to the module. Now I'm putting together the complete implementation that handles the topological ordering and callback firing.\n\nWriting propagation logic... Writing the ComputeCell class... Verifying the implementation against the spec requirements and checking edge cases like diamond dependencies, callback removal, and ensuring callbacks fire only when values actually change rather than on every propagation cycle. = max(2,2) = 2). When X changes, the affected cells are {B, C, A}, and sorting by level gives [B, C, A], so B and C recompute first before A recomputes once. This confirms the approach is working correctly.",
